  "What does it mean to raise a complex number to a negative integer power using De Moivre's Theorem?": "",
  "It is undefined for complex numbers": "",
  "Only the modulus changes; the argument stays the same": "",
  "The modulus is raised to the negative power (reciprocal) and the argument is multiplied by the negative integer": "",
  "The result is always a real number": "",
  "De Moivre's Theorem works for all integers, including negatives: [r cis(theta)]^(-n) = r^(-n) cis(-n*theta) = (1/r^n) cis(-n*theta). This is equivalent to taking the reciprocal of the nth power.": "",
  "What is the relationship between De Moivre's Theorem and Euler's formula?": "",
  "They are unrelated theorems": "",
  "De Moivre's Theorem follows directly from Euler's formula e^(i*theta) = cos(theta) + i sin(theta) by raising both sides to the nth power": "",
  "Euler's formula is a special case of De Moivre's Theorem when n = 1": "",
  "De Moivre's Theorem only works in degrees while Euler's formula uses radians": "",
  "De Moivre's Theorem can be derived from Euler's formula: (e^(i*theta))^n = e^(i*n*theta), which gives (cos(theta) + i sin(theta))^n = cos(n*theta) + i sin(n*theta).": "",
